body:
actually... i've discovered that remote apps (such as caldav etc) don't appear to call setupbackends() anytime after init(), so basically, they remain broken for those use cases.

each app that requires authentication should call setupbackends(), but probably an easier fix would be for authentication plugins that require the 'user_backends' config option to call setupbackends() during load.

for user_external, here's a patch that allows it to work for remote apps:
```diff
--- user_external/appinfo/app.php-orig  2013-04-03 01:03:47.000000000 -0700
+++ user_external/appinfo/app.php   2013-04-06 18:14:18.863120871 -0700
@@ -2,3 +2,6 @@
 oc::$classpath['oc_user_imap']='apps/user_external/lib/imap.php';
 oc::$classpath['oc_user_smb']='apps/user_external/lib/smb.php';
 oc::$classpath['oc_user_ftp']='apps/user_external/lib/ftp.php';
+
+// this isn't always called after backend is loaded
+oc_user::setupbackends();
```

owncloud: owncloud 5.0.11 rc2

i studied a bit the problem, i come from the related bug https://github.com/owncloud/core/issues/1826 . in that bug the problem described here results in the impossibility to authenticate on remote.php to access the contacts if one uses imap authentication, for this reason i believe its important to fix the bug this ticket refers to.

here is an analysis and a possible solution.

*analysis*

oc::init() calls oc_user::setupbackends() before the user_external app is registered. this generates the error message above because the auth apps are not loaded (because the global variable $runtime_noapps is set to true both in remote.php and index.php).

when accessing from index.php the authentication works because in oc::handlerequest(), oc_user::setupbackends() is called again.

when accessing from remote.php oc_user::setupbackends() is not called by the core. it's the task of the each app to setup the auth backends. for instance the contacts app loads the authentication apps in apps/contacts/appinfo/remote.php but it doesn't call oc_user::setupbackends so external authentication doesn't work.

*possible solution*

one possible solution would be to do this fix in lib/base.php:

```

global $runtime_noapps;
global $runtime_apptypes;
if (!$runtime_noapps) {
        if ($runtime_apptypes) {
                oc_app::loadapps($runtime_apptypes);
        } else {
                oc_app::loadapps();
        }
}

+ oc_app::loadapps('authentication');

//setup extra user backends
oc_user::setupbackends();


```

and remove all calls to oc_user::setupbackends() elsewhere (also the one in lib/user.php).

by looking at the source code it seems that this should not open up other issues, but since i'm not familiar with the codebase i might be overlooking something. in particular if there is an entry point to the app that doesn't include the lib/base.php file before using oc_user then in that case auth will not work correctly.

the other drawback of this approach is that the authentication apps are loaded even if the request being processed doesn't require authentication, resulting in some unnecessary overhead.

@blizzz
ok thanks for feedback. but is this a good reason to have multiple ways to register backends? or is one of them deprecated? currently i only write some patches for this app and connect it with our own group-system so i don't know the full api of owncloud.

regards

@clemenssahs the standard way for user/group backends is to use

```
oc_user::usebackend($myuserbackend);
oc_group::usebackend($mygroupbackend);
```

user_external is somewhat atypical. you may have a look on how user_ldap is doing it.
